"### File Structure
```
MusicStreaming/
│
├── app.py
├── data/
│   ├── songs.txt
│   ├── artists.txt
│   ├── albums.txt
│   ├── genres.txt
│   ├── playlists.txt
│   └── playlist_songs.txt
│
├── templates/
│   ├── dashboard.html
│   ├── song_catalog.html
│   ├── song_details.html
│   ├── playlists.html
│   ├── playlist_details.html
│   ├── create_playlist.html
│   ├── albums.html
│   ├── album_details.html
│   ├── artists.html
│   └── genres.html
│
└── static/
    ├── css/
    │   └── styles.css
    ├── js/
    │   └── scripts.js
    └── images/
        └── (cover arts, artist photos, album covers)
```

### File Descriptions
```
app.py
- The main backend Python application file.
- Implements the web server, routing, and all business logic.
- Handles reading from and writing to local text files in the 'data' directory.
- Manages data parsing, searching, filtering, and playlist management.
- Serves the HTML templates with dynamic data.

data/
- Contains all the local text files storing the application's data as specified.
- Each file corresponds to a data entity (songs, artists, albums, genres, playlists, playlist songs).

templates/
- Contains all HTML template files for the 10 pages defined in the requirements.
- Each template corresponds to a page (Dashboard, Song Catalog, Song Details, etc.).
- Templates use placeholders for dynamic content populated by app.py.

static/
- Contains static assets such as CSS stylesheets, JavaScript files, and images.
- css/styles.css: Styles for consistent UI design across pages.
- js/scripts.js: Client-side scripts for interactivity (e.g., button actions, filtering).
- images/: Stores cover art, artist photos, and album covers referenced in the UI.

Notes:
- Backend logic is consolidated in a single Python file (app.py) since the application complexity is moderate.
- Frontend is separated into templates and static assets for maintainability and clarity.
- Data files are kept in a dedicated 'data' folder to isolate persistent storage from code.
